4.0 of 5 bubbles
Halong Bay - how to buy tickets
Halong Bay is beautiful and awesome. A must see when visiting North Vietnam. It's also a big time moneymachine with lots of scam.
Below is some bulletpoints info that might help you to select tour and prize without prebooking.
1. Same programme, same rute and same overnight stay points on Halong Bay for all companies regardless of the star rating (1 to 5)
2. All cataloque pics of cruiseships are taken when the ship was built and do not reflect the real thing.
3. There are 10 ticket offices in Hanoi for every 1 cruiseship (500+) that have licence to Halong Bay. Most of the sinh cafe travel offices closes around 20:00 - the hotels are 24/7.
4. All ticket offices or hotels gives instantly 25% off the cataloque prize just to lure you in. From here it's up to you to bargain it lower down. 50% seems to be lowest they will accept. (will take some time and skills)
5. Budget are 40-100$/pax
Midrange are 100-150$/pax
Luxury from 150$+/pax
6. Tickets salesman will always tell you it's the last room to put pressure on you - NOT true!!! there are always another cruise ready to take you on until the last hour before departure.
7. The nextdoor ticket offices (or hotel) always knocks another 10% off your bargained prize just to get you to purchase at his place instead.
8. All cruises serves good and plenty of food and makes money on drinks and tips. You can bring your own water and snack, but not softdrinks and beverages.
9. If you ask about the boat age, they will give the date it was bought from another company and not the date it was launch.
10. Lot of tour companies change names - making it difficult to do research on trip advisor or web.
11. Most people do 3days/2nights as the 2days/1night programme is very tight with multible 1 hour activities.
12. Cooking classes is rolling a fresh spring roll on the way back.
13. Everything outside the beaten path can be purchased.
14. Be prepared for a lot of other tourists.
15. If you corner a salesman in a lie he will suddenly no longer understand you or anything else and you will get stock.
Good luck and enjoy it when you get there - it's amazing place.
Written March 10, 2015
dcgiuk
Norwich, UK48 contributions
Scam city, this place is a hole
We decided not to get on a tour but get a bus to Bai Chay and from the moment we got on the bus it didn't feel right.
The guy who was a tour guide on the bus looked off like he was either on drugs, extremely tired or drunk, very strange his words were slurred and there was something just off about it.
The bus was slow, sometimes ridiculously slow, at times knowing I could get out and cycle faster. This is done on purpose so that when you arrive they can apologise that you cannot do what you thought you were able to do, twice on the bus a Spanish guy from the group got up and complained to the tour guide about this scam.
We had not been off the bus for more than 10 seconds and a lady tout approached us and seem to know we were not on a tour, how she knew we don't know, maybe we were pointed out, we hadn't moved from the large group. She followed us to the counter where you can buy your own tickets, the ladies behind the counters seemed reluctant to sell us anything, presumably because she was with us and there is now we understand a Mafia-like culture here and it starts from the moment you purchase your tour in Hanoi.
So we went across the road to eat some dinner and done some research and quickly concluded we were going to be ripped off or at least wondering when it was going to happen. Stories about going to Cat Ba island, hitting the north end and being stranded from public transport save for some men motorbikes drastically overcharging did nothing to quash our fears of this place.
Bai Chay has some very odd characters in it, odd behaviour and nothing reassuring, easily the weirdest and worst place we've been to in our so far 8 month tour. My fianc√©e hit the spot when she said "this feels like a typical border-town", people who only see you as a wallet from which they need to try and empty. We didn't have anything like this feeling in Hanoi and hopefully not in the rest of Vietnam, for sure most people like this country so I think it's just this awful place.
I wish we'd have done more research; being a number 1 attraction and a UNESCO site no less we just figured on going there and navigating ourselves. It must be great right? Wrong.
I think we just saved ourselves a lot of money and stress. Do your research and figure out whether just because it's a world wonder, no. 1 on TripAdvisor and a UNESCO site that you should go or whether that actually this place has been ruined by greed and scamming.
We knew it was going to be hazy but we arrived here and could hardly see anything for sure January is not the time to visit this place.
UNESCO should also re-evaluate whether this place should be given such status, an awful place with awful people.
We're now waiting for a bus out of here, by now we've no faith that the man we talked to has arranged a bus for us or not, 4pm, 7 minutes to go, keep your fingers crossed we don't have to spend the night here!
Written January 23, 2015
